<html>
<head>
<title>Application users</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Application users</h1>
<p></p>

<div id="properties">
<h2>User properties</h2>
<ul>
	<li id="userSave_user_userName">
	<p><b>User name</b> is unique within the application.</p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_status">
	<p><b>State</b> specifies if the user is active, disabled or was deleted from the system. Only <b>active</b> users can log in.</p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_firstName">
	<p>User's <b>first name</b></p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_lastName">
	<p>User's <b>last name</b></p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_displayName">
	<p><b>Display name:</b> Displaying person's names does not follow any international convention. Specify this field on how person's name should display in application.</p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_mail">
	<p>Person's <b>email address</b>: The email should be unique to the system, but there's no limit. Two or more users can have the same email address.</p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_description">
	<p><b>User description</b> usually contains information about user's affiliation to application or organization, but you should store any information about the
	user you deem relevant.</p>
	</li>
	<li id="userSave_user_department">
	<p><b>Department</b> where person works within the organization.</p>
	</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div id="access-tags">
<h2>User Access tags</h2>
<p>Access tags were introduced to allow granting global read rights to users. Any tagged entity that is contains one of the tags listed in user's tag list will be visible to
the user.</p>
<span id="userSave_user_accessTags">
<p>Enter a new tag value. To remove a tag value, clear all text and <b>Update</b> user properties by clicking the Update button above (or press &lt;Enter&gt;).</p> 
</span>

</div>
</body>
</html>